# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: general-product-safety-regulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/95-ec] This **list of European Union Directives** is ordered by theme to follow EU law.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/95-ec] For a date based list, see the Category:European Union directives by number.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/95-ec] From 1 January 1992 to 31 December 2014, numbers assigned by the General Secretariat of the Council followed adoption, for instance: Directive 2010/75/EU.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/95-ec] Some older directives had an ordinal number in their name, for instance: "First Council Directive 73/239/EEC".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/95-ec] The proposed standards were to be developed by October 2022.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/95-ec] Another proposed amendment to the 2013 directive was put forward by the Commission in April 2016 concerning disclosure of corporate tax information on a country-by-country basis.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer protection is linked to the idea of **consumer rights** and to the formation of consumer organizations, which help consumers make better choices in the marketplace and pursue complaints against businesses.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] A consumer is defined as someone who acquires goods or services for direct use or ownership rather than for resale or use in production and manufacturing.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer interests can also serve consumers, consistent with economic efficiency, but this topic is treated in competition law.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer protection can also be asserted via non-government organizations and individuals as consumer activism.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer protection law or consumer law is considered as an area of law that regulates private law relationships between individual consumers and the businesses that sell those goods and services.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer protection covers a wide range of topics, including but not necessarily limited to product liability, privacy rights, unfair business practices, fraud, misrepresentation, and other consumer/business interactions.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] It is a way of preventing frauds and scams from service and sales contracts, eligible fraud, bill collector regulation, pricing, utility turnoffs, consolidation, personal loans that may lead to bankruptcy.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] There have been some arguments that consumer law is also a better way to engage in large-scale redistribution than tax law because it does not necessitate legislation and can be more efficient, given the complexities of tax law.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In Australia, the corresponding agency is the Australian Competition & Consumer Commission or the individual State Consumer Affairs agencies.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Australian Securities & Investments Commission has responsibility for consumer protection regulation of financial services and products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] However, in practice, it does so through privately run EDR schemes such as the Australian Financial Complaints Authority.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In Brazil, consumer protection is regulated by the Consumer's Defense Code (Código de Defesa do Consumidor), as mandated by the 1988 Constitution of Brazil.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Instead, the defense has to bring forward evidence that they are innocent.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In the case of Brazil, they narrowly define what consumers, suppliers, products, and services are, so that they can protect consumers from international channels trade laws and protect them from negligence and misconduct from international suppliers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In Colombia, consumer protection is primarily governed by Law 1480 of 2011 (Estatuto del Consumidor), which replaced the previous consumer protection regime and established a comprehensive framework for the protection of consumers' rights.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The law guarantees consumers the right to receive quality products and services, accurate information, effective warranties, and legal protection against abusive contractual clauses.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer protection in Colombia extends beyond physical products to cover the quality of service provision, including healthcare services.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Superintendencia de Industria y Comercio (SIC) is the main government authority responsible for enforcing consumer protection regulations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The SIC exercises jurisdictional functions, allowing it to adjudicate consumer protection claims directly, including warranty reimbursement proceedings, without requiring consumers to resort to ordinary courts.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In addition to its jurisdictional role, the SIC holds the power to impose administrative sanctions on businesses that violate consumers' rights and to investigate unfair commercial practices.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Several regulations in the European Union are concerned with consumer protection, including the Regulation on general product safety (GPSR) and the Directive (EU) 2024/2853 on liability for defective products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Germany, as a member state of the European Union, is bound by the consumer protection directives of the European Union; residents may be directly bound by EU regulations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] A minister of the federal cabinet is responsible for consumer rights and protection (*Verbraucherschutzminister*).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In the current cabinet of Friedrich Merz, this is Carsten Schneider.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] When issuing public warnings about products and services, the issuing authority has to take into account that this affects the supplier's constitutionally protected economic liberty, see Bundesverwaltungsgericht (Federal Administrative Court) Case 3 C 34.84, 71 BVerwGE 183.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In India, consumer protection is specified in The Consumer Protection Act, 2019.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Under this law, Separate Consumer Dispute Redress Forums have been set up throughout India in every district in which a consumer can file their complaint on a simple paper with nominal court fees and their complaint will be decided by the Presiding Officer of the District Level.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The complaint can be filed by both the consumer of a goods as well as of the services.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] An appeal could be filed to the State Consumer Disputes Redress Commissions and after that to the National Consumer Disputes Redressal Commissiaon (NCDRC).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The procedures in these tribunals are relatively less formal and more people-friendly and they also take less time to decide upon a consumer dispute when compared to the years-long time taken by the traditional Indian judiciary.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In recent years, many effective judgments have been passed by some state and National Consumer Forums.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Indian Contract Act, 1872 lays down the conditions in which promises made by parties to a contract will be legally binding on each other.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] It also lays down the remedies available to the aggregate party if the other party fails to honor their promise.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Sale of Goods Act of 1930 provides some safeguards to buyers of goods if goods purchased do not fulfill the express or implied conditions and warranties.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Agriculture Produce Act of 1937 act provides grade standards for agricultural commodities and livestock products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] It specifies the conditions which govern the use of standards and lays down the procedure for grading, marking, and packaging of agricultural produce.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The quality mark provided under the act is known as AGMARK-Agriculture Marketing.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Nigerian government must protect its people from any form of harm to human health through the use and purchase of items to meet daily needs.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In a nutshell, it is empowered to eliminate hazardous & substandard goods from the market.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Provide speedy redress to consumer complaints and petition arisen from fraud, unfair practice, and exploitation of the consumer.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] On 5 February 2019, the President of Nigeria, Muhammadu Buhari, assented to the new Federal Competition and Consumer Protection Commission Bill, 2018.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Thus, the bill became a law of the Federal Republic of Nigeria and binding on entities and organizations so specified in the Act.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Modern Taiwanese law has been heavily influenced by the European civil law systems, particularly German and Swiss law.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Civil Code in Taiwan contains five books: General Principles, Obligations, Rights over Things, Family, and Succession.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The second book of the Code, the Book of Obligations, provided the basis from which consumers could bring product liability actions prior to the enactment of the CPL.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Consumer Protection Law (CPL) in Taiwan, as promulgated on 11 January 1994, and effective on 13 January 1993, specifically protects the interests and safety of customers using the products or services provided by business operators.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Consumer Protection Commission of Executive Yuan serves as an ombudsman supervising, coordinating, reporting any unsafe products/services, and periodically reviewing the legislation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The main consumer protection laws in the UK are the Consumer Protection Act 1987 and the Consumer Rights Act 2015.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The United Kingdom has left the European Union, but during the transition period (until end of 2020) the UK was still bound by directives of the European Union.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Specifics of the division of roles between the EU and the UK are detailed here.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Domestic UK laws originated within the ambit of contract and tort but, with the influence of EU law, it is emerging as an independent area of law.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In many circumstances, where domestic law is in question, the matter is judicially treated as tort, contract, restitution or even criminal law.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Consumer protection issues were dealt with by the Office of Fair Trading before 2014.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Since then, the Competition and Markets Authority has taken on this role.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In the United States a variety of laws at both the federal and state levels have regulated consumer affairs since the early 20th century.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Among them are the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act, Fair Debt Collection Practices Act, the Fair Credit Reporting Act, Truth in Lending Act, Fair Credit Billing Act, and the Gramm–Leach–Bliley Act.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Federal consumer protection laws are mainly enforced by the Federal Trade Commission, the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, the Food and Drug Administration, and the U.S.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] At the state level, many states have adopted the Uniform Deceptive Trade Practices Act including, but not limited to, Delaware, Illinois, Maine, and Nebraska.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The deceptive trade practices prohibited by the Uniform Act can be roughly subdivided into conduct involving either a) unfair or fraudulent business practices and b) untrue or misleading advertising.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The Uniform Act contains a private remedy with attorneys fees for prevailing parties where the losing party "willfully engaged in the trade practice knowing it to be deceptive".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Missouri has a similar statute called the Merchandising Practices Act.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Also, the majority of states have a Department of Consumer Affairs devoted to regulating certain industries and protecting consumers who use goods and services from those industries.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] For example, in California, the California Department of Consumer Affairs regulates about 2.3 million professionals in over 230 different professions, through its forty regulatory entities.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] In addition, California encourages its consumers to act as private attorneys general through the liberal provisions of its Consumers Legal Remedies Act.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] State and federal laws provide for "cooling off" periods giving consumers the right to cancel contracts within a certain time period for several specified types of transactions, potentially including transactions entered into at home, and warranty and repair services contracts.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Other states have been the leaders in specific aspects of consumer protection.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] For example, Florida, Delaware, and Minnesota have legislated requirements that contracts be written at reasonable readability levels as a large proportion of contracts cannot be understood by most consumers who sign them.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Considering the state of Massachusetts, the Massachusetts Consumer Protection Law, MGL 93A, clearly highlights the rights and violations of consumer protection law in the state.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The chapter explains what actions are considered illegal under the law for which a party can seek monetary damages from the other party at fault.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] The laws under MGL 93A prohibit activities that relate to overpricing to a consumer and the use of "Bait and Switch" techniques.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] A court will award the plaintiff the damages if they can prove the (1) defendant knowingly and intentionally violated the MGL 93A agreement or (2) the defendant would not "grant relief in bad faith" knowing that the actions violated the MGL 93A agreement.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/consumer-protection] Additionally, failure to disclose refund/ return policy, warranties, and critical information about the product/service are all in violation of the legislation, and can result in triple damages and lawyer fees.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Decisions about distribution need to be taken in line with a company's overall strategic vision and mission.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Developing a coherent distribution plan is a central component of strategic planning.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] At the strategic level, as well as deciding whether to distribute directly or via a distribution network, there are three broad approaches to distribution, namely mass, selective and exclusive distribution.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The number and type of intermediaries selected largely depends on the strategic approach.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The overall distribution channel should also add value to the consumer overall.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Distribution is fundamentally concerned with ensuring that products reach target customers in the most direct and cost-efficient manner.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In the case of services, distribution is principally concerned with access.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Before designing a distribution system, the supplier needs to determine what distribution channel to achieve in broad terms.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The approach to distributing products or services depends on a number of factors including the type of product, especially perishability; the market served; the geographic scope of operations and the firm's overall mission and vision.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The process of setting out a broad statement of the aims and objectives of a distribution channel is a strategic level decision.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In consumer markets, another key strategic level decision is whether to use a push or pull strategy.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In a *push strategy*, the marketer uses intensive advertising and incentives aimed at distributors, especially retailers and wholesalers, with the expectation that they will stock the product or brand, and that consumers will purchase it when they see it in stores.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In contrast, in a *pull strategy*, the marketer promotes the product directly to consumers hoping that they will pressure retailers to stock the product or brand, thereby pulling it through the distribution channel.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The choice of a push or pull strategy has important implications for advertising and promotion.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Distribution of products takes place through a marketing channel, also known as a distribution channel.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] A marketing channel is the people, organizations, and activities necessary to transfer the ownership of goods from the point of production to the point of consumption.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] It is the way products get to the end-user, the consumer.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] This is mostly accomplished through merchant retailers or wholesalers or, in the international context, by importers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In certain specialist markets, agents or brokers may become involved in the marketing channel: for example in the insurance sector, the European Union has noted that "insurance and reinsurance intermediaries play a central role in the distribution of insurance and reinsurance products" .
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The EU introduced the Insurance Distribution Directive in 2016 to enhance a level of harmonisation in this market across EU member states.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] A firm can design any number of channels they require to reach customers efficiently and effectively.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Channels can be distinguished by the number of intermediaries between producer and consumer.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] If there are no intermediaries then this is known as a *zero-level* distribution system or direct marketing.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] A *level one* (sometimes called *one-tier*) channel has a single intermediary.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] A *level two* (alternatively a *two-tier*) channel has two intermediaries, and so on.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] This flow is typically represented as being manufacturer to retailer to consumer, but may involve other types of intermediaries.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In practice, distribution systems for perishable goods tend to be shorter - direct or single intermediary, because of the need to reduce the time a product spends in transit or in storage.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In other cases, distribution systems can become quite complex involving many levels and different types of intermediaries.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In practice, many organizations use a mix of different channels; a direct sales force may call on larger customers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] This may be complemented with other agents to cover smaller customers and prospects.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] When a single organization uses a variety of different channels to reach its markets, this is known as a *multi-channel* distribution network.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In addition, online retailing or e-commerce is leading to disintermediation, the removal of intermediaries from a supply chain.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Retailing via smartphone or m-commerce is also a growth area.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The firm's marketing department needs to design the most suitable channels for the firm's products, then select appropriate channel members or intermediaries.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] An organization may need to train staff of intermediaries and motivate the intermediary to sell the firm's products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The firm should monitor the channel's performance over time and modify the channel to enhance performance.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] To motivate intermediaries the firm can use positive actions, such as offering higher margins to the intermediary, special deals, premiums and allowances for advertising or display.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] On the other hand, negative actions may be necessary, such as threatening to cut back on margin, or hold back delivery of product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Care must be exercised when considering negative actions as these may fall foul of regulations and can contribute to a public backlash and a public relations disaster.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Manufacturer complacency has been highlighted as a risk leading distributors to move their business to other supply lines.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Channel conflict can arise when one intermediary's actions prevent another intermediary from achieving their objectives.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Vertical channel conflict occurs between the levels within a channel, and horizontal channel conflict occurs between intermediaries at the same level within a channel.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Channel conflict is a perennial problem.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] There are risks that a powerful channel member may coordinate the interests of the channel for personal gain.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Territories are often seen as a source of conflict, sometimes because boundaries are only loosely defined.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Hart refers to the extensive development of these guilds and the "Training Schools" which they operated, converting these into a radio-based program from 1942.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Hart, who worked for the supplier, put this experience forward to the American Marketing Association as "an outstanding example of manufacturer-distributor collaboration on an industry-wide basis".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Companies wishing to grow through sales to new markets may need to identify and develop relationships with local distributors, for example to support export to new markets.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] In southeast Asia, for example, many distributors have a head office in Singapore which can be used by manufacturers outside the region to increase their regional market penetration and grow sales.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Channel-switching is the action of consumers switching from one type of channel intermediary to a different type of intermediary for their purchases.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Examples include switching from brick-and-mortar stores to online catalogues and e-commerce providers; switching from grocery stores to convenience stores or switching from top tier department stores to mass market discount outlets.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] A number of factors have led to an increase in channel switching behaviour; the growth of e-commerce, the globalization of markets, the advent of category killers (such as Officeworks and Kids 'R Us) as well as changes in the legal or statutory environment.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] For the consumer, channel switching offers a more diverse shopping experience, which may concern some sellers by its potential to erode market share.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Evidence of channel switching can suggest that disruptive forces are at play, and that consumer behaviour is undergoing fundamental changes.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] A consumer may be prompted to switch channels when the product or service can be found at cheaper prices, when superior models become available, when a wider range is offered, or simply because it is more convenient to shop through a different channel (e.g. online or one-stop shopping).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] As a hedge against market share losses due to switching behaviour, some retailers engage in multi-channel retailing.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The emergence of a service-dominant logic perspective has focused scholarly attention on how distribution networks serve to create customer value and to consider how value is co-created by all the players within the distribution chain, including the value created by customers themselves.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] This emphasis on value-creation is contributing to a change in terminology surrounding distribution processes; "distribution networks" are often termed *value-chains* while "distribution centers" are often termed *customer fulfillment centers*.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] For example, the retail giant Amazon, which utilizes both direct online distribution alongside bricks and mortar stores, now calls its distribution centers "customer fulfillment centers".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Although the term "customer fulfillment center" has been criticized on the grounds that it is a neologism, its use is becoming increasingly mainstream as it slowly makes its way into introductory marketing textbooks.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Disintermediation occurs when manufacturers or service providers eliminate intermediaries from the distribution network and deal directly with purchasers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Disintermediation is found in industries where radically new types of channel intermediaries displace traditional distributors.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] The widespread public acceptance of online shopping has been a major trigger for disintermediation in some industries.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/distribution-marketing] Certain types of traditional intermediaries are dropping by the wayside.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/economic-operator] An **economic operator** is a business or other organisation which supplies goods, works or services within the context of market operations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/economic-operator] The term is used in public procurement to cover suppliers, contractors and service providers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/economic-operator] "any person or public entity or group of such persons and entities, including any temporary association of undertakings, which offers the execution of works or a work, the supply of products or the provision of services on the market".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/economic-operator] The terms 'business' or 'undertaking' would therefore have been inappropriate and the term 'economic operator' was therefore adopted.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/economic-operator] It is used merely in the interest of simplification.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The mark indicates that the product may be traded freely in any part of the European Economic Area, regardless of its country of origin.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] It consists of the CE letter pair and, if applicable, the four digit identification number of the notified body involved in the conformity assessment procedure.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The CE mark on a product indicates that the manufacturer or importer of that product affirms its compliance with the relevant EU legislation and the product may be sold anywhere in the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] It is a criminal offence to affix a CE mark to a product that is not compliant or to offer such a product for sale.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] For example, most electrical products must comply with the Low Voltage Directive and the EMC Directive, among others; toys must comply with the Toy Safety Directive.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In the case of electrical products, several later norms such as the Restriction of Hazardous Substances Directive (RoHS) and Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive (WEEE) are relevant in addition to the Low Voltage Directive and EMC Directive.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The exact significance of the CE mark therefore depends on when it was applied to a specific unit.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The marking does not indicate EEA manufacture or that the EU or another authority has approved a product as safe or conformant.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The EU requirements may include safety, health, and environmental protection.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] If stipulated in any EU product legislation, assessment by a Notified Body or manufacture according to a certified production quality system may be required.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Where relevant, the CE mark is followed by the registration number of the notified body involved in conformity assessment.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Not all products need CE marking to be traded in the EEA; only product categories subject to relevant directives or regulations are required (and allowed) to bear CE marking.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Although it has been suggested that the CE letter pair is an abbreviation of ***conformité européenne*** (as used, for example, in a written question in the European Parliament), this meaning appears to be a backronym.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] None of the defining EU Directives or EU Regulations give this association.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] When the Commission replied to the written question, they did not repeat or acknowledge those words.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] However, in a 2014 press release, the Commission gave CE as an abbreviation of *conformité européenne*.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] This is the only quasi-validation of the term that has been publicly released by a European authority.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] CE marking is mandatory for certain product groups intended for sale within the European Union, the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), and Turkey.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] As Northern Ireland (a region of the UK) remains aligned to the European Single Market under the Northern Ireland Protocol, CE marking remains mandatory for products placed on the market there, and the British UKCA mark is not required.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The formal legal status of the CE mark is set out in various EU Directives and Regulations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The underlying principles are explained in the Commission's "Blue Guide".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Responsibility for CE marking lies with whoever puts the product on the market in the EU, i.e. an EU-based manufacturer, the importer or distributor of a product made outside the EU, or an EU-based office of a non-EU manufacturer.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The manufacturer of a product affixes the CE marking to it but has to take certain obligatory steps before the product can bear CE marking.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The manufacturer must carry out a conformity assessment, set up a technical file, and sign a Declaration stipulated by the leading legislation for the product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The documentation has to be made available to authorities on request.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Importers of products have to verify that the manufacturer outside the EU has undertaken the necessary steps and that the documentation is available upon request.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Importers should also make sure that contact with the manufacturer can always be established.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Distributors must be able to demonstrate to national authorities that they have acted with due care and they must have affirmation from the manufacturer or importer that the necessary measures have been taken.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] If importers or distributors market the products under their own name, they take over the manufacturer's responsibilities.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In this case they must have sufficient information on the design and production of the product, as they will be assuming the legal responsibility when they affix the CE marking.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] A guide to the implementation of directives and regulations based on the New Approach and the Global Approach (the "Blue Guide") was first published by the European Union in 2000.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Updated versions were published on 28 February 2014 and 26 July 2016.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Depending on the level of risk of the product, the CE marking is affixed to a product by the manufacturer or authorized representative who needs to ensure that the product meets all the CE marking requirements.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In some cases, if a product has minimal risk, it can be self-certified by a manufacturer making a declaration of conformity and affixing the CE marking to their own product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Self-certification exists only for products that have a minimal risk for their use, and this is clearly foreseen in the relevant directive and regulation according to the product "category".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Choose the conformity assessment procedure from the modules called out by the directive or the regulation for the product according to each category (level of risk) involved.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] There are several modules available for the Conformity Assessment Procedures, but only a few of them involve self-certification.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The most of these procedure require a "type Approval" and a Production conformity assessment by a Notified Body.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] All procedures (modules) of certification are as listed below which are derivered from Article 5.1.7 of "Blue Guide".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The level of risk is defined by the "category" of each equipment.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The higher the category, the higher the risk.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] After defining the category, the manufacturer, in order to obtain certification, shall then apply the relevant procedures for the specific category of the product or choose the relevant procedures for a higher-category product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The manufacturer, after insuring that the relevant modules for the product category have been applied, will affix the CE mark and draw up a Declaration of Conformity.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The Declaration of Conformity contains a description of the product, the directive(s) and regulation(s) applied, the product category for each directive or regulation, the module chosen, and the name and registration number of the notified body involved in certification procedures (models).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Notified bodies involved in certification procedures are organizations that have been nominated by a member state (according to an accreditation procedure) and have been notified by the European Commission.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] These notified bodies act as Independent Inspection organizations and carry out the procedures as listed in the relevant Modules applied as stated by the relevant directives and regulations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] A manufacturer can choose any notified body (notified for the certain directive or regulation and relevant Modules) in any Member State of the European Union.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The first step is to identify whether the product needs to bear CE marking or not.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Not all products are required to bear CE marking, only the products that fall within the scope of at least one of the sectoral norms (directives and regulations) requiring CE marking.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] There are more than 20 sectoral product norms requiring CE marking covering, but not limited to, products such as electrical equipment, machines, medical devices, toys, pressure equipment, PPE, wireless devices and construction products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Identifying which norm(s) may be applicable, as there may be more than one, involves a simple exercise of reading the scope of each norm to establish which apply to the product (Such as the "Low Voltage Directive," 2014/35/EU).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] If the product does not fall within the scope of any of the sectoral norm, then the product does not need to bear CE marking (and, indeed, must not bear CE marking).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Each norm has slightly different methods of demonstrating conformity depending on the classification of the product and its intended use.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Every Directive or Regulation has a number of 'essential requirements' that the product has to meet before being placed on the market.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The best way to demonstrate that these essential requirements have been met is by meeting the requirements of an applicable 'harmonised standard,’ which offer a presumption of conformity to the essential requirements, although the use of standards usually remains voluntary.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Harmonised standards can be identified by searching the 'Official Journal' on the European Commission's website, or by visiting the New Approach website established by the European Commission and EFTA with the European Standardisation Organisations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The process is not always a self-declaration process, there are various 'attestation routes' to conformity depending on the Directive or Regulation and classification of the product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Many products (such as invasive medical devices, or fire alarm and extinguisher systems, Pressure Equipment, Lifts etc.) in most cases, have a mandatory requirement for the involvement of an authorised third party e.g. a "notified body".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] When all of the requirements have been established, the conformity of the product to the essential requirements of the norm(s) needs to be assessed.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] This usually involves assessment and/or testing, and may include an evaluation of the conformity of the product to the harmonised standard(s) identified in step 2.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Technical documentation, usually referred to as the technical file, relating to the product or range of products needs to be compiled.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] This information should cover every aspect relating to conformity and is likely to include details of the design, development and manufacture of the product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] When the manufacturer, importer or authorised representative is satisfied that their product conforms to the applicable norms, an EU declaration of conformity must be completed or, for partly completed machinery under the Machinery Directive, an ECU declaration of incorporation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Under the General Product Safety Regulation (EU) 2023/988 (GPSR), the EU declaration of conformity is a mandatory legal document in which the manufacturer or authorised representative declares that a product complies with all applicable safety requirements.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The declaration is part of the product’s technical documentation and must be submitted to competent authorities on request.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] There are numerous 'Agreements on Mutual Recognition of Conformity Assessment' between the European Union and other countries such as the US, Japan, Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Israel.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Consequently, CE marking is now found on many products from these countries.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Japan has its own marking known as the Conformity Mark.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Switzerland and Turkey (which are not members of the EEA) also require products to bear CE marking as an affirmation of conformity.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] When the manufacturer of a machine puts the CE marking, it engages itself and guarantees, that it makes all the tests, assessments and evaluation on the product to conform to all the requirements of *all* the norms that apply to its product.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The European Commission is aware that CE markings, like other certifications marks, are misused.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] CE marking is sometimes affixed to products that do not fulfill the legal requirements and conditions, or it is affixed to products for which it is not required.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In one case it was reported that "Chinese manufacturers were submitting well-engineered electrical products to obtain conformity testing reports, but then removing non-essential components in production to reduce costs".
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] There are also cases in which the product complies with the applicable requirements, but the form, dimensions, or proportions of the mark itself are not as specified in the legislation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In 2008, a logo very similar to CE marking was alleged to exist and to stand for *China Export* because some Chinese manufacturers apply it to their products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] However, the European Commission says that this is a misconception.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The matter was raised at the European Parliament in 2008.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The Commission responded that it was unaware of the existence of any "Chinese Export" mark and that, in its view, the misunderstanding had arisen because a producer had failed to respect the precise dimensions and proportions of the mark as prescribed in the legislation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The Commission was also aware of fraudulent misuse of the mark on products that did not comply with the standards, but that this is a separate issue.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] It had initiated the procedure to register CE marking as a Community collective trademark, and was in discussion with Chinese authorities to ensure compliance with EU legislation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Chinese (and other non-EU) manufacturers are permitted to use the CE mark provided that the goods have been manufactured in accordance with the relevant EU directives and regulations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Nevertheless, and despite the Commission's assurance that it is without foundation, this urban myth continues to propagate on many websites.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In March 2017, another question was put to the European Commission on the statistics of the fraudulent use of the CE mark, reasserting the "China Export" myth.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In reply, the Commission notes that it is the responsibility of Member States to take legal action on infringements; the Commission does not have statistics on the penalties that were imposed by Member States for the improper use of the CE marking.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In an IEEE conference paper studying the origins and evolution of the claim, the author concludes there is no evidence of a fraudulent "China Export" sign.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In addition, similar "fraudulent" marking can be found in many European and American made products which do not show apparent noncompliance.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Typesetting C and E too near to each other is probably just a typesetting mistake.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The possibly earliest mention of "China Export" can be found on a Finnish fishing-themed discussion forum on year 2004.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The author suspects the origins start from a joke: someone has invented a funny meaning for the abbreviation CE, from which the claim has evolved as oral history and turned into a widespread myth.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Repeating the myth as a European parliamentary question has reinforced the credibility of the myth.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Directive 2014/35/EU, the "Low Voltage Directive", specifically excludes (amongst other things) *plugs and socket outlets for domestic use* which are not covered by any Union norm and therefore should not be CE marked.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Throughout the EU, as in other jurisdictions, the control of *plugs and socket outlets for domestic use* is subject to national regulations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] It is fairly common to see domestic sockets (and adaptors) that have an inbuilt 5 volt USB-A power supply socket in addition to conventional 'two-pin + earth' AC sockets.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] These sockets must be CE marked, but the CE mark applies to the 5 volt converter *only* and not the rest of the socket or adaptor.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] This is comparable to dedicated 5 volt power supplies.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] There are mechanisms in place to ensure that the CE marking is put on products correctly.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Controlling products bearing CE marking is the responsibility of public authorities in member states, in cooperation with the European Commission.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Citizens may contact national market surveillance authorities if the misuse of the CE marking is suspected or if a product's safety is questioned.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] In the UK, sale of any product that carries a CE mark that is not so approved, or outside the scope of approval is a specific offence under Section 1 of the Trade Descriptions Act 1968.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The seller of such an article is as equally guilty as the manufacturer or importer.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Ignorance as to the true status of the sold item is no defence against a prosecution (strict liability).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Under the Act, the misrepresentation is that the sold item conforms to a specification that it does not or that there is no such specification to which it can conform.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The procedures, measures and sanctions applying to counterfeiting of the CE marking vary according to the respective member state's national administrative and penal legislation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] Depending on the seriousness of the crime, economic operators may be liable to a fine and, in some circumstances, imprisonment.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] However, if the product is not regarded as an imminent safety risk, the manufacturer may be given an opportunity to ensure that the product is in conformity with the applicable legislation before being forced to take the product off the market.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The mark does not have a Unicode code point.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] According to the Unicode principles, rendering the mark is a computer font design choice for the two ordinary upper-case letters, C and E, with a specific kerning arrangement.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-declaration-of-conformity] The exact geometry that constitutes the mark is provided in the vector graphics files available from the European Commission.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] A **Digital Product Passport** (DPP), sometimes referred to as the product’s technical file, is a digital record mandated by EU law that consolidates essential information on a product’s identity, compliance, safety, and sustainability.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] Originating under the Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation (ESPR), the DPP is intended to make supply chains more transparent, and to complement safety obligations under the General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] Digital Product Passports can be accessed through data carriers such as QR codes, barcodes, NFC tags, or other machine-readable identifiers that connect a physical product to structured digital information.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The DPP is intended to improve product traceability and facilitate rapid conformity checks by customs and market surveillance authorities.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] It also supports circular economy objectives, such as repair, reuse, and recycling, by recording materials, components, lifespan, and disposal guidance.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] In addition, it provides consumers with information on product origin, compliance, user safety, and lifecycle management.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The Digital Product Passport serves as a digital record containing documentation that demonstrates a product’s compliance with EU requirements.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The Declaration of Conformity (DoC) is a critical element of this documentation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The technical documentation must be made available to market surveillance authorities upon request and should enable authorities to assess whether a product is safe.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] For many product categories, such as toys, electrical equipment, or furniture, this may include evidence of testing to harmonised European standards (for example, EN 71, EN 60335, or EN 12520).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The DPP ensures that essential product information can be shared efficiently across the supply chain and with authorities.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The implementation of the DPP follows a phased approach under the Ecodesign for Sustainable Products Regulation, beginning with product categories identified as having significant environmental impact, including batteries, textiles, electronics, and furniture.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] Pilot initiatives began in 2024, with full deployment expected between 2025 and 2030.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-digital-product-passport] The European Commission will define specific DPP requirements for different product groups through delegated acts, and a central EU registry is anticipated by mid-2026.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The **General Product Safety Regulation** (**GPSR**) is a European regulation on consumer protection.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] It replaces Directive 2001/95/EC on general product safety.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The regulation is intended to ensure that products placed on the market in the European internal market do not endanger the health and safety of consumers through a high level of consumer protection.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The regulation applies to products placed on the market or made available in the EU.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] If certain other harmonized legal provisions apply to these products, they are fully or partially exempt from certain obligations, such as the assessment through an internal risk analysis.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Some categories of products, like medicinal products, are exempt.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The scope of the regulation includes economic operators such as fulfillment service providers and online marketplace operators.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Non-EU Manufacturers may name an authorised representative in the European Union as a contact point for market surveillance authorities.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Under Article 5 of the General Product Safety Regulation, manufacturers and other economic operators must ensure that products placed or made available on the EU market are safe.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] To comply, they must conduct an internal risk analysis and prepare technical documentation demonstrating conformity.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The risk analysis process involves a structured evaluation of hazards associated with a product’s design, materials, and intended use, supported by relevant EU legislation and standards.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The analysis must categorise risks according to severity (e.g., critical, major, minor), document mitigation measures taken (such as design improvements, warnings, user instructions), and evaluate the adequacy of labeling, packaging, and instructions to reduce residual risks to an acceptable level.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Products that conform to applicable harmonised standards benefit from a presumption of conformity with the general safety requirement for the risks covered by those standards.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Where no standards exist, operators must rely on documented alternative methodologies, best practices, and a detailed justification of safety measures.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Economic operators must maintain these records as part of the product’s technical file and present them to national authorities upon request.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Failure to conduct a sufficient risk assessment or to maintain adequate documentation may lead to enforcement actions such as product recalls, fines, or market restrictions.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The information must be affixed on the product itself or, where impractical, on packaging or in accompanying documents.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Digital labels (e.g., QR codes linking to online content) can complement (but cannot replace) these physical labeling requirements.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] In addition, Article 19 requires online and distance sellers to clearly display manufacturer or authorised representative information, product identification, and any applicable warnings on their website or online interface.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Under the General Product Safety Regulation, manufacturers and other economic operators must compile and maintain technical documentation demonstrating product compliance with safety requirements.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] This documentation, also referred to as a technical file, serves as the key evidence that a product meets the general safety requirement of the regulation and may be held in digital form as a Digital Product Passport (DPP) when applicable.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] While certain product information may optionally be provided digitally, such as in a QR code, the technical documentation itself must be available to authorities upon request.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The Declaration of Conformity is a key element of this documentation, providing a formal statement that the product meets applicable EU legislation.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Article 22 of the GPSR introduces new requirements for online marketplaces.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Marketplaces must also cooperate with regulatory bodies to remove unsafe products swiftly and prevent repeat violations.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The GPSR also includes provisions for distance selling that apply to online providers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] These providers must register on the Safety Gate portal.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Online providers of products covered by the GPSR are also required to fulfill information obligations for consumers.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Article 22 additionally names specific obligations of providers of online marketplaces that are related to product safety and information.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] To enhance accountability, GPSR mandates that non-EU manufacturers appoint an **EU-based economic operator** to ensure compliance.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] This can be an EU-based importer, distributor, or an authorized representative.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] If a non-EU manufacturer does not designate an EU-based economic operator, the importer or distributor automatically assumes legal responsibility for product compliance.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The General Product Safety Regulation confirms that the manufacturer is primarily liable for ensuring that products placed on the EU market are safe and compliant.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] Article 4 of Directive 85/374/EEC states that manufacturers are liable for damage caused by defective products.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] While the GPSR requires economic operators such as authorised representatives, importers, and distributors to assist market surveillance authorities, this does not make them liable unless they meet the definition of “producer” under EU law (for example, by branding a product).
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The responsible person or authorised representative is a regulatory contact and documentation holder, not the party liable for consumer compensation under the Product Liability Directive.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] If the manufacturer is outside the EU and no importer is identifiable, liability may extend to other economic operators to ensure consumer protection.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] This regulation applies to all products within its scope that are placed on the market from 13 December 2024.
[src:general-product-safety-regulation/eu-responsible-person] The making available on the market of products covered by Directive 2001/95/EC, which comply with that directive and were placed on the market before 13 December 2024, shall not be impeded by EU member states.
